Introduction

Using a search string on Scopus, I retrieved 128 peer-reviewed scientific papers on social sustainability assessment indicators in agri-food systems. After a throughout reading of the papers to identify and structure social sustainability indicators, I am using Natural Language Processing (NLP) to avoid the subjectivity of traditional content analysis in comparing discourses. This Rmarkdown shows some of the steps involved in the NLP process.

Text cleaning

To quantitively analyse text data, there is a need to impose a certain structure on it. Tokenisation consisted of breaking texts into minimal meaningful units (words in this case) called tokens. In addition, lemmatisation was used to convert each word to its original form (e.g., do, does, did, done > do). Other cleaning steps, such as removing stop words (words that do not give us any significant insight from the texts) and removing URLs, numbers, and punctuation, were also performed.

# remove punctuation
corp <- tm_map(corp, content_transformer(removePunctuation))

#remove numbers
corp <- tm_map(corp, content_transformer(removeNumbers))

# transform to lower characters
corp <- tm_map(corp, content_transformer(tolower))

# strip white spaces 
corp <- tm_map(corp, content_transformer(stripWhitespace))

# keep the stem of words

Text mining

Frequent words in the publications

Manual lemmatisation function

Before looking at the most frequent words used in the publications, I will performe some further text cleaning by writing a function to manually handle some spelling differences between British and American English (e.g., Labor has been changed to Labour), and variations of the same word are counted as one.

paper_tokens <- tidy_corp %>% unnest_tokens("word", text)


manual_lemma <- function(w) {
  # I am using "w" to mean "word"
  #w <- gsub("Labour", "labour", w)
  w <- gsub("labor", "labour", w)
  w <- gsub("agricultural", "agriculture", w)
  w <- gsub("environmental", "environment", w)
  w <- gsub("sustainable", "sustainability", w)
  return(w)
}
# perfom manual lemmatization
paper_tokens$word <- sapply(paper_tokens$word, manual_lemma )

There is roughly the same groups of keywords used by researchers before and after the SDGs. However, word frequencies have more than tripled in the 6 years since 2015 (note that the number of publications has doubled compared to the time before the SDGs, i.e.1994-2014). Except words such as sustainability, agriculture, indicators, which are the most used for obvious reasons (all papers deal with sustainability assessment in agriculture), the only words related to social sustainability indicators that appeared in the top 20 frequent words are food (food security), water (access to water) and land (land tenure).

How has the usage of the word social evolved over time?

We notice a stark increase of the word social in the literature after the introduction of the SDGs.

The historical trend analysis of the top eight SSI keywords (Figure 8) suggests an impact of the introduction of the SDGs. The SSI keywords have been used more often since the advent of the SDGs in 2015 and mostly peaked in 2019. While it can be argued that the SSI keyword food is not always used to refer to an indicator related to food security in publications, it is by far the most frequent word among the SSI keywords - even more so than social itself, which was added on Figure 8 for comparative purposes. As backed by the readings, food security is a prominent social sustainability issue, especially after the adoption of the SDGs. The SSI keyword food is followed by land, water, and gender. The use of the SSI keyword health is relatively low. The words participation and education are the least mentioned. The frequency of the word participation over time is striking in that it exposes an apparent contradiction with the content analysis result that participation is the most important indicator at most geographic scales and in most agri-food systems.

Word embeddings

Word embeddings are a way to represent text data as vectors of numbers based on a huge corpus of text, capturing semantic meaning from words context [2, p. 106]. Word vectors were built based on a famous quote by JR Firth: You shall know a word by the company it keeps [3, p. 11].

The GloVe Algo

There are two prominent algorithms for word embeddings, word2vec and GloVe. The GloVe algorithm for Global Vectors was used as it takes both global statistics of a word and local statistics in a corpus to come up with word vectors. This application generally follows the implementation by Dmitriy Selivanov, which youll definitely want to spend some time with. You can read more about the algorithm here.

The algorithm uses the co-occurrence matrix to derive a semantic relationship between words. Considering a corpus of V words, the co-occurrence matrix X will be a V x V matrix, where the i-th row and the j-th column of X, \(X_{i,j}\), indicate how often word i has co-occurred with word j (Pennington et al., 2014). Once the word vectors are known, a widely used measure to compare them is the cosine similarity which is the cosine of the angle between word vectors in a given space and ranges from 1 (most distant) to 1 (closest) [4]. For two word vectors wx,wy, the cosine similarity is computed using the following formula:

\[cos(wx, wy) = \frac{wx\cdot\ wy}{||wx||\cdot\ ||wy||}\]

In the next step I will create a vocabulary, a set of words for which I want to learn word vectors.

#create tokens from the papers

before <- before %>%
  select(id, text) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

after <- after %>%
  select(id, text) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)

# transform the tokens into a list 
before_ls <- list(before$word)

after_ls <- list(after$word)



# Create iterator over tokens
it_b <- itoken(before_ls, progressbar = FALSE)

it_a <- itoken(after_ls, progressbar = FALSE)

#create vocabulary from the papers' tokens
before_vocab <- create_vocabulary(it_b)

after_vocab <- create_vocabulary(it_a)

#keep only words which appear at least twenty times for meaningful word vector calculation
before_vocab <- prune_vocabulary(before_vocab, term_count_min = 20L)

after_vocab <- prune_vocabulary(after_vocab, term_count_min = 20L)
# maps words to indices
vectorizer_b <- vocab_vectorizer(before_vocab)

vectorizer_a <- vocab_vectorizer(after_vocab)

# use window of 10 for context words
tcm_before <- create_tcm(it_b, vectorizer_b, skip_grams_window = 10L)

tcm_after <- create_tcm(it_a, vectorizer_a, skip_grams_window = 10L)

In the next code chunk I calculate the global vectors for words in the corpora before the SDGs.

set.seed(4005)

glove = GlobalVectors$new(rank = 100, x_max = 10)

before_wv_main <- glove$fit_transform(tcm_before, n_iter = 100, convergence_tol = 0.00001)

 #dim(before_wv_main)

before_wv_context <- glove$components

 #dim(before_wv_context)

# Either word-vectors matrices could work, but the developers of the technique
# suggest the sum/mean may work better
before_word_vectors <- before_wv_main + t(before_wv_context)

In the next code chunk I calculate the global vectors for words in the corpora after the SDGs.

set.seed(4005)

glove = GlobalVectors$new(rank = 100, x_max = 10)

after_wv_main <- glove$fit_transform(tcm_after, n_iter = 300, convergence_tol = 0.00001)

 #dim(after_wv_main)

after_wv_context <- glove$components

 #dim(after_wv_context)

# Either word-vectors matrices could work, but the developers of the technique
# suggest the sum/mean may work better
after_word_vectors <- after_wv_main + t(after_wv_context)

The word embedding reveals that most of the selected SSI keywords were closer to after the SDGs, with water and participation having moved the closest to Difficult. The apparent increase in the use of selected SSI keywords after the SDGs (in the historical trend analysis) and the results of the word embedding model show that these topics (therefore the associated social sustainability indicators) appear to be progressively seen as more challenging in the literature and are of interest to researchers.

It was not possible to compute the cosine similarity of the word gender in the scale before the SDGs.To understand why, the word frequencies were consulted and revealed that the word gender was mentioned only 4 times before the SDGs compared to 312 times after the SDGs. This suggests that gender equity issues are seemingly gaining traction in assessing the sustainability of agri-food systems.

The T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding

Training word embedding is an unsupervised machine learning process, and as such, there are no right answers to test the result [4]. Yet, validating the word embedding learned from our text collections is necessary before using them as the basis for a serious analysis. The T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) algorithm represents words with high-dimensional vectors (100-D in our case) in a two-dimensional space [5] that can help to visually validate the model.

  • t-SNE before the SDGs

tsne_b <- Rtsne(before_word_vectors, perplexity = 45)

Some findings from the content analysis

I synthesized all the indicators retrieved from the literature in an Excel workbook.Indicators are categorized according to the spatial scale, the agri-food system (context), and the level on the results chain of the Theory of Change (ToC). The spatial scale is simply the human geographic scale at which indicators are selected and analysed in each study. The agri-food system refers to the context of the production system in which the indicator is measured. The ToC levels (input, activities, output, outcome, impact) were used to give an overview of the chain relationship between the indicators, from those related to the inputs to the impact through the activities, outputs and outcomes.

Ill import the Excel file in the following code chunk.

#import indicators database 

indicators <- read_excel("Indicators_DataBase.xlsx")

data <- 
read_excel("Indicators_DataBase.xlsx", sheet = "Sheet2") %>%
  #filter(Context != "Conceptual") %>%
  group_by(Toc, Label) %>%
  count() %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  data.frame()

  
#data$Toc <- factor(data, levels = c("Input", "Activity", "Output", 
            #"Outcome", "Impact") )


data <- data %>%
  mutate(Toc = factor(Toc, levels = c("Input", "Activity", "Output", 
           "Outcome", "Impact"))) %>%
  arrange(Toc)

#levels(data$Toc)
#data

# Set a number of 'empty bar' to add at the end of each group
empty_bar <- 2
to_add <- data.frame( matrix(NA, empty_bar*nlevels(data$Toc), ncol(data)) )
colnames(to_add) <- colnames(data)
to_add$Toc <- rep(levels(data$Toc), each=empty_bar)

data <- rbind(data, to_add)
data <- data %>% arrange(Toc, n)
data$id <- seq(1, nrow(data)) 


# Get the name and the y position of each label
label_data <- data
number_of_bar <- nrow(label_data)
angle <- 90 - 360 * (label_data$id-0.5) /number_of_bar     # I substract 0.5 because the letter must have the angle of the center of the bars. Not extreme right(1) or extreme left (0)
label_data$hjust <- ifelse( angle < -90, 1, 0)
label_data$angle <- ifelse(angle < -90, angle+180, angle)
 
# prepare a data frame for base lines
base_data <- data %>% 
  group_by(Toc) %>% 
  summarize(start=min(id), end=max(id) - empty_bar) %>% 
  rowwise() %>% 
  mutate(title=mean(c(start, end)))
 
# prepare a data frame for grid (scales)
grid_data <- base_data
grid_data$end <- grid_data$end[ c(nrow(grid_data), 1:nrow(grid_data)-1)] + 1
grid_data$start <- grid_data$start - 1
grid_data <- grid_data[-1,]
  • Circular bar plot
# Make the plot
p <- data %>%

  ggplot(aes(x=as.factor(id), y=n, fill = Toc)) +       # Note that id is a factor. If x is numeric, there is some space between the first bar
  
  geom_bar(aes(x=as.factor(id), y=n, fill= Toc), stat="identity", alpha=0.5) +
  
  # Add a val=40/30/20/10 lines. I do it at the beginning to make sure barplots are OVER it.
  geom_segment(data=grid_data, aes(x = end, y = 40, xend = start, yend = 40), colour = "grey", alpha=1, size=0.3 , inherit.aes = FALSE ) +
  geom_segment(data=grid_data, aes(x = end, y = 30, xend = start, yend = 30), colour = "grey", alpha=1, size=0.3 , inherit.aes = FALSE ) +
  geom_segment(data=grid_data, aes(x = end, y = 20, xend = start, yend = 20), colour = "grey", alpha=1, size=0.3 , inherit.aes = FALSE ) +
  geom_segment(data=grid_data, aes(x = end, y = 10, xend = start, yend = 10), colour = "grey", alpha=1, size=0.3 , inherit.aes = FALSE ) +
  
  # Add text showing the value of each 40/30/20/10 lines
  ggplot2::annotate("text", x = rep(max(data$id),4), y = c(10, 20, 30, 40), label = c("10", "20", "30", "40") , color="grey", size=3 , angle=0, fontface="bold", hjust=1) +
